orig_sop:
Open my latest created issue that has feature in its title to check if it is closed
1. Click the "Issues" icon (located directly to the right of the plus sign icon) in the top purple navigation bar.
2. Click on the third gray tab labeled "All" at the top.
3. Click the search box at the top of the page (to the right of the "Assignee" tag).
4. Enter in the keyword "feature".
5. Click the down arrow to the right of the search bar to open the sort by dropdown menu.
6. From the dropdown, click on "Created date".
7. Click on the first sorted search result that includes the keyword.
8. From this page, you can find if the issue is closed.
new_sop:
Based on the workflow demonstration and the provided instructions, here is the updated Standard Operating Procedure. 

1. Click the "Issues" icon (square icon with list lines, located on the right side next to the merge requests icon) in the top global navigation bar.
2. Click on the search text field located at the top of the Issues dashboard (containing the text "Search GitLab" or current filters).
3. Type the keyword "feature" into the search text field.
4. Press the "Enter" key on your keyboard to submit the search query.
5. Click on the sort dropdown button labeled "Created date" (or the current sort criteria) located above the list of issues on the right side.
6. Click on the "Created date" option in the dropdown menu to ensure the list is sorted by the date created.
7. Click on the title of the first issue in the sorted list (this corresponds to the latest created issue matching the search criteria).

orig_sop:
Which customer has placed 2 orders in the entire history?
1. Click on "Reports" in the left bar of the page.
2. Click on "Order Count" under the "Customers" tab.
3. In the "From" field, click on the calendar icon.
4. From the calendar, click on the dropdown next to the year, and select the earliest year in the list, which is "1923".
5. For the month, select January from the month dropdown.
6. For the date, select 1, the first date in January.
7. In the "To" field, click on the calender icon.
8. Click on today's date.
9. Click on the "Show By" dropdown.
10. Click on "Year".
11. Click on the "Refresh" button next to the filter list.
12. From the displayed information, report the customer(s) who has placed 2 orders in the entire history.
new_sop:
1. Click on the link labeled "REPORTS" in the left navigation sidebar.
2. Click on the link labeled "Order Count" under the "Customers" section in the popup menu.
3. Click on the calendar icon button located inside the "From" input field.
4. Click on the year dropdown menu in the header of the calendar widget.
5. Scroll to the top of the dropdown list until the year "1923" is visible.
6. Click on the text labeled "1923" in the dropdown list.
7. Click on the month dropdown menu in the header of the calendar widget.
8. Click on the text labeled "Jan" in the dropdown list.
9. Click on the text labeled "1" in the calendar grid to select the first day of the month.
10. Click on the calendar icon button located inside the "To" input field.
11. Click on the text labeled "27" (or the number corresponding to the current date) in the calendar grid.
12. Click on the dropdown menu labeled "Show By" to the right of the date fields.
13. Click on the option labeled "Year" in the dropdown menu.
14. Click on the button labeled "Refresh" to update the report.
15. Scroll up the page to view the customer data in the "Order Count Report" table.

orig_sop:
Show me the name of the customers who have expressed dissatisfaction with Chloe tank
1. Click on the “CATALOG” button in the dark gray column on the left hand side of the page.
2. Click on “Products” in the pop up menu, located under the bolded heading “Catalog”.
3. Click into the search box, located above the products table.
4. Type in “Chloe tank”.
5. Press enter.
6. Since there were no products found, we will modify our search query.
7. Delete “ jacket”.
8. Press enter.
9. Click on the product name of the relevant product. The product name is located in the “Name” column of the given row.
10. Scroll down to the “Product Reviews” section.
11. Click on the “Product Reviews” section to expand its contents.
12. Scroll down to view all reviews.
13. The reviews that express dissatisfaction can be found in this reviews table. Expressions of dissatisfaction can be found in the meaning of text in the “Title” and “Review” columns of a given row.
14. Since a review of interest by a user with a nickname doesn’t include their full name, we will try to find this user’s full name.
15. Click on the blue text “Edit”, located in the rightmost column of the row containing the review of interest.
16. The user’s full name is not displayed. Hence, we will simply record their nickname, located in the box directly to the right of the bolded text “Nickname”.
new_sop:
Based on the provided screenshots and action log, here is the improved Standard Operating Procedure.

1. Click on the button labeled "CATALOG" in the left sidebar navigation menu.
2. Click on the text labeled "Products" under the "Catalog" heading in the menu that appears.
3. Click on the text field labeled "Search by keyword" located above the product list.
4. Type "Chloe tank" into the text field.
5. Press the "Enter" key.
6. If the search yields no results (indicated by the message "We couldn't find any records"), delete the text " tank" from the "Search by keyword" text field.
7. Press the "Enter" key.
8. Click on the link labeled "Chloe Compete Tank" in the "Name" column of the product list.
9. Scroll down to the section labeled "Product Reviews".
10. Click on the "Product Reviews" section header to expand its contents.
11. Scroll down to view the table of reviews.
12. Click on the link labeled "Edit" in the "Action" column for the review that expresses dissatisfaction (specifically the review with the Title "Not for non-petite").

orig_sop:
What is the price range for products from Amazon basic?
1. Click the blue "Advanced Search" button located under the larger search bar on the top right of the page.
2. Enter "Amazon basic" in the "Product Name" box.
3. Click the blue "Search" button.
4. Select the "Sort By" box and click "Price" on the dropdown.
5. The price under the first item (bolded text, above the blue "Add to Cart" button) is the lower bound of the price range.
6. Click the up arrow (located on the right of the sort by box) to switch it to a down arrow.
7. The price under the first item that says "Amazon Basic in the title" (price is in bolded text, above the blue "Add to Cart" button) is the upper bound of the price range.
new_sop:
Based on the workflow demonstration and the provided rubric, here is the updated Standard Operating Procedure.

1. Click on the link labeled "Advanced Search" located below the search bar on the top right of the page.
2. Click on the text field labeled "Product Name" within the "Search Settings" section.
3. Type "Amazon basic" into the "Product Name" text field.
4. Click on the button labeled "Search" located at the bottom of the "Search Settings" form. If the button is not visible, scroll down to find it.
5. Click on the dropdown menu labeled "Sort By" located above the product grid on the right side of the page.
6. Click on the option labeled "Price" in the dropdown menu. If the arrow icon located to the right of the dropdown is pointing down, click it to ensure the sort order is ascending (lowest price first).
7. Click on the arrow icon located to the right of the "Sort By" dropdown menu to switch the sort order to descending (highest price first).

orig_sop:
Show me the name of the customers who have expressed dissatisfaction with tanks products?
1. Click on the “MARKETING” button in the dark gray column on the left hand side of the page.
2. Click on “All Reviews” in the pop up menu, located under the bolded heading “User Content”.
3. Click into the search box below the column heading “Product”.
4. Type in “tank”.
5. Press enter.
6. Since we have 27 results, which we can see above the “Created” column heading, we will make it easier for us to see all reviews by displaying them all on one page.

8. Select “30” from the drop down menu.
9. Scroll down through each row of the product table.
10. Return the names of customers dissatisfied with tank products. Each row is a separate review for a product with “tank” in its name. You can find customer names in the “Nickname” column of a given row, and you can find whether a customer is dissatisfied by analyzing the text in the “Title” and “Review” columns of a given row.
new_sop:
Based on the workflow demonstration and the SOP Rubric provided, here is the updated Standard Operating Procedure.

1. **Click** on the link labeled "MARKETING" located in the dark gray navigation sidebar on the left side of the screen.
2. **Click** on the text labeled "All Reviews" located under the "User Content" heading in the pop-up menu that appears.
3. **Click** on the empty text field located directly below the "Product" column header in the specific review table.
4. **Type** the text "tank" into the selected text field.
5. **Press** the "Enter" key on the keyboard to filter the table results.
6. **Click** on the "per page" dropdown menu (displaying a number like "20") located above the table grid on the right-hand side.
7. **Click** on the number "30" in the dropdown list to ensure all results appear on a single page (Edge Case: If the "Records found" count adjacent to the dropdown is higher than 30, click a higher number like "50" or "100" instead).
8. **Scroll** down through the table rows to view the "Nickname", "Title", and "Review" columns to identify customers expressing dissatisfaction.

orig_sop:
What's the total number of items sold in the most recent 7 orders?
1. Click on the “REPORTS” button in the dark gray column on the left hand side of the page.
2. Click on “Orders” in the pop up menu, located under the heading “Sales”.
3. Click into the “From” text field, located on the left side of the page.
4. Type in “1/1/23”.
5. Click into the “To” text field, located directly to the right of the “From” text field.
6. Type in the current date.
7. Click on the orange button “Show Report”, located at the top right of the page.
8. Scroll to the bottom of the page.
9. The sum of numbers in the “Sales Items” column, the third column of the table, for the 8th, 7th, 6th, 5th, 4th, 3rd, and 2nd to last rows is the total number of items sold in the most recent 7 orders.
new_sop:
Based on the provided screenshots and workflow demonstration, here is the improved Standard Operating Procedure.

1. Click on the icon labeled "REPORTS" in the sidebar navigation menu on the left side of the screen.
2. Click on the link labeled "Orders" located under the "Sales" heading in the menu that appears.
    *   *Edge Case:* If the menu closes before you can click "Orders", click "REPORTS" again to reopen it.
3. Click on the text field labeled "From" in the "Filter" section on the left side of the page.
4. Type "1/1/23" into the "From" text field.
5. Click on the text field labeled "To" located directly to the right of the "From" text field in the "Filter" section.
6. Type "1/13/24" into the "To" text field.
7. Click on the orange button labeled "Show Report" located in the top right corner of the page.
    *   *Edge Case:* If the report data does not refresh, ensure the date format matches the placeholder (M/D/YY) and try again.
8. Scroll to the bottom of the page to view the "Orders Report" table.
    *   *Edge Case:* If the table is empty, broaden the date range in the "From" and "To" fields to include more past dates.
9. The total number of items sold in the most recent 7 orders is found by summing the values in the "Sales Items" column (3rd column) for the last 7 rows in the table (excluding the final row labeled "Total").
    *   *Edge Case:* If the "Orders" column (2nd column) displays a value greater than 1 for any row, count rows from the bottom upwards until exactly 7 orders are accounted for, rather than simply selecting 7 rows.

orig_sop:
Show me the customers who have expressed dissatisfaction with Antonia racer tank?
1. Click on the “CATALOG” button in the dark gray column on the left hand side of the page.
2. Click on “Products” in the pop up menu, located under the bolded heading “Catalog”.
3. Click into the search box, located above the products table.
4. Type in “Antonia racer tank”.
5. Press enter.
6. Click on the product name of the relevant product. The product name is located in the “Name” column of the given row.
7. Scroll down to the “Product Reviews” section.
8. Click on the “Product Reviews” section to expand its contents.
9. Scroll down to view all reviews.
10. The reviews that express dissatisfaction can be found in this reviews table. Expressions of dissatisfaction can be found in the meaning of text in the “Title” and “Review” columns of a given row.
11. Since a review of interest by a user with a nickname doesn’t include their full name, we will try to find this user’s full name.
12. Click on the blue text “Edit”, located in the rightmost column of the row containing the review of interest.
13. The user’s full name is not displayed. Hence, we will simply record their nickname, located in the box directly to the right of the bolded text “Nickname”.
14. Click on the “Back” button, located near the top of the page and directly to the left of the “Delete Review” button.
15. Scroll down to the “Product Reviews” section.
16. Click on the “Product Reviews” section to expand its contents.
17. Scroll down to view all reviews.
18. Since a review of interest by a user with a nickname doesn’t include their full name, we will try to find this user’s full name.
19. Click on the blue text “Edit”, located in the rightmost column of the row containing the review of interest.
20. The user’s full name is not displayed. Hence, we will simply record their nickname, located in the box directly to the right of the bolded text “Nickname”.
new_sop:
Based on the provided screenshots and actions, here is the improved Standard Operating Procedure (SOP).

1. Click on the "CATALOG" menu item located in the left sidebar navigation.
2. Click on the "Products" link located in the "CATALOG" submenu.
3. Click on the text field labeled "Search by keyword" located above the product data grid.
4. Type "Antonia racer tank" into the text field.
5. Press the "Enter" key on the keyboard to submit the search.
6. Click on the text "Antonia Racer Tank" located in the "Name" column of the search results row.
7. Scroll down the page until the "Product Reviews" section header is visible.
8. Click on the "Product Reviews" section header to expand the list of reviews.
    *   *Edge Case:* If the section is already expanded (contents are visible), skip this step.
9. Click on the "Edit" link located in the "Action" column for the review with the title "Zero support/modesty".
    *   *Relevance:* This step allows you to view the details of the first customer who expressed dissatisfaction.
10. Click on the "Back" button located at the top left of the "Edit Review" page to return to the product details.
11. Scroll down the page until the "Product Reviews" section header is visible.
12. Click on the "Product Reviews" section header to expand the list of reviews.
    *   *Edge Case:* If the section is already expanded (contents are visible), skip this step.
13. Click on the "Edit" link located in the "Action" column for the review with the title "Not for high impact".
    *   *Relevance:* This step allows you to view the details of the second customer who expressed dissatisfaction.
